snippet: After the win, the question was why the military leaders who controlled Myanmar would voluntarily hand over power. The answer seems to be that they never thought they would.
abstract: News Analysis; government officials and members of Myanmar's military-backed governing party say in interviews that landslide victory of Daw Aung San Suu Kyi's party in national elections came as surprise; prior to elections there was longstanding question of whether military leaders would relinquish control, but in election's aftermath it is clear that they never thought it was possible that Aung San Suu Kyi's party would win.

byline.original: By THOMAS FULLER and WAI MOE
byline.contributor: Reporting was contributed by Seth Mydans, Austin Ramzy, Eaint Thiri Thu and Saw Nang.

lead_paragraph: After the win, the question was why the military leaders who controlled Myanmar would voluntarily hand over power. The answer seems to be that they never thought they would.

headline.print_headline: One Group Caught Off Guard by Vote in Myanmar: The Longtime Rulers
headline.main: Victory by Aung San Suu Kyi’s Party Catches One Group Off Guard: The Government
